\title{On-demand zeroing}

\p{When a process asks for new heap memory, the OS must guarantee the returned pages contain zeros (to avoid leaking other processes' data). The naive implementation zeroes the page at allocation time. \em{On-demand zeroing} defers that work to first touch: until the process actually accesses a freshly-allocated page, no zero-fill happens.}

\p{The OS marks the page as not-present in the [[WALE]]. The first access traps as a [[CXFM]], the handler zeroes a physical page, installs it in the PTE, and resumes. Heap memory that is allocated but never used costs nothing.}
